\section{Define a simple Entity-Relationship notation}


\exobox{Exercise 1}{
The task is to define two classes {\tt EntityType} and {\tt RelationshipType}. The class {\tt RelationshipType}
shall have an attribute {\tt role}  with value {\tt EntityType}.
}

\begin{verbatim}
EntityType end

RelationshipType with
  attribute
     role: EntityType
end
\end{verbatim}


Enter the definitions into the {\em Telos Editor\/} window and store them to the ConceptBase server with the "Tell"
function.

\exobox{Exercise 2}{
Add to {\tt EntityType} an attribute {\tt attr} with value {\tt Domain}. Also define {\tt Domain} as an object without
attributes.
}

\begin{verbatim}
EntityType with
  attribute
    attr: Domain
end

Domain end
\end{verbatim}


This provides us with a very simple entity-relationship language. It just allows to define entity types with attributes, and relationship types with role links. Entity attributes are restristed to domains. So we need to specify the allowed domains.

\exobox{Exercise 3}{
Specify {\tt Integer}  and {\tt String} as domains, i.e. as instances of the class {\tt Domain}.
}

\begin{verbatim}
Integer in Domain end
String in Domain end
\end{verbatim}



The classes {\tt Integer} and {\tt String} are predefined in ConceptBase. Any integer number occurring in an 
object definition will automatically be an instance of {\tt Integer}. Likewise any double-quoted string will be
regarded as an instance of {\tt String}. 

\exobox{Exercise 4}{
Specify a new domain {\tt Date}. Include "2009-05-19" and "2001-01-01" as two possible values for dates.
}

\begin{verbatim}
Date in Domain end
"2009-05-19" in Date end
"2001-01-01" in Date end
\end{verbatim}

The object {\tt Date} is not predefined in ConceptBase. Hence, we need to take care ourselves about the 
set of possible values (=instances of {\tt Date}).

After these exercises, you can visualize the current state with the graph editor. User {\tt RelationshipType}
as start object. The graph editor is started from CBIva via the menu item "Browse / Graph Editor".
Expand the outgoing attributes of {\tt RelationshipType} (right mouse button) and select "Show all". Do the same
with {\tt EntityType}. For {\tt Domain}, show the instances. For {\tt Date}, show the instances as well.

\cbfigure{cbiva3}{10cm}{Graphical display of the ER language}

The graph window shows already three abstraction levels: the objects "2009-05-19" and "2001-01-01" are at the lowest
abstraction level (data level). The objects {\tt Date}, {\tt Integer}, and {\tt String} are classes (model level), and
the objects {\tt RelationshipType}, {\tt EntityType}, and {\tt Domain} are meta classes (notation level).


