\section{Define an example process model}

Recall the insurance scenario. Now we need to represent a 
workflow in this domain with our newly defined process modeing notation.

\exobox{Exercise 11}{
Claim handling starts with an insurance agent receiving the claim.
Afterwards, the policy is checked. Afterwards, either a payment is proposed 
or an assessor is assigned. The assessor assesses the damage. On that basis,
the insurance agent proposes a payment. After proposing the payment, we either can 
continue with processing the payment (customers accepts the proposal), or
we need to iterate i.e. check again the policy and possibly repropose a new payment.
The workflow is finished after processing the payment.
}

\begin{verbatim}
start in Task with
  successor
     n: receiveClaim
end

receiveClaim in Task with
   successor
     n: checkPolicy
end

checkPolicy in Task with
    successor
      n1: assignAssessor;
      n2: proposePayment
end

assignAssessor in Task with
     successor
       n: assessDamage
end

assessDamage in Task with
   successor
     n: proposePayment
end

proposePayment in Task with
    successor
      accept: processPayment;
      reject: checkPolicy
end

processPayment in Task with
   successor
     n: finish
end

finish in Task end


Assessor in Agent with
  executes
    t1: assessDamage
end

InsuranceAgent in Agent with
   executes
     t1: receiveClaim;
     t2: proposePayment
end
\end{verbatim}


\exobox{Exercise 12}{
Ask the two queries {\tt LoopTask} and {\tt AgentWithSplitResponsibility}.
}

The answer to {\tt LoopTask} is {\tt checkPolicy}, {\tt assignAssessor},
{\tt assessDamage}, {\tt proposePayment}. 
The answer to {\tt AgentWithSplitResponsibility} is {\tt InsuranceAgent}, {\tt Assessor}. Note that
the task {\tt assessDamage} is in a loop with {\tt proposePayment}. Hence, a sequence
{\tt assessDamage}-{\tt proposePayment}-{\tt checkPolicy}-{\tt assignAssessor}-{\tt assessDamage} is possible and is the
reason to classify both agents into the query class {\tt AgentWithSplitResponsibility}.

You can also visualize the results of the queries by the graph editor. The example process model
together with the classification to the two query classes is shown in figure \ref{fig:cbiva6}.

\cbfigure{cbiva6}{10cm}{Classifying a process model via query classes}

The dotted green links are derived instantiations. So, an object that is in the answer set
of a query class is regarded as a derived instance of that query class. Indeed, query classes
are classes where the instances are derived via the membership condition of the query class.

