\section{Link the two notations}

We have created two simple notations, one for data modeling and the scond for process modeling.
Now let us combine these two. The most natural way appears to regard object types
(entity types and relationship types) as possible inputs and outputs of tasks in a process
model.

\exobox{Exercise 13}{
Define a new construct {\tt ObjectType} that generalizes {\tt EntityType} and
{\tt RelationshipType}.
}

\begin{verbatim}
ObjectType end
EntityType isA ObjectType end
RelationshipType isA ObjectType end
\end{verbatim}

So, this was easy. We now can link the two notations via {\tt ObjectType}.

\exobox{Exercise 14}{
Define object type as possible input/output of tasks in process models.
}

\begin{verbatim}
Task with
 attribute
    input: ObjectType;
    output: ObjectType
end
\end{verbatim}

Attributes in ConceptBase are by default multi-valued, ie.\ they can have zero, one or many
values. This is exaclty what we want in this case. 

We finalize this tutorial by attaching some objects types as input/output of tasks.

\exobox{Exercise 15}{
Define some of the object types of exercise 5 as input/output of the process model of
exercise 11.
}
\begin{verbatim}
receiveClaim with
  output o1: Claim
end

checkPolicy with
  input i1: claim_policy
end
\end{verbatim}

\section{Conclusions}

In this tutorial, we defined two simple notations, one for data modeling, another for process modeling.
We defined queries to analyze process models for non-trivial patterns, building on a newly defined
construct for transitivity. We created example models for both notations. Finally, we linked the two
notations to form an integrated method for data and process modeling.

The two notations were both very simple. For example, the ER notation lacks cardinalities of role links.
The process modeling notation cannot represent parallel splits. Adding the missing construct
would not require too much effort. The interested reader is referred to the CB-Forum
(\url{http://conceptbase.sourceforge.net/CB-Forum.html})
for extended examples.


